  <section class="cra-section">
    <div class="cra-section-label">
      <span class="cra-section-label-num">04</span>
      <span class="cra-section-label-text">Decision Log</span>
      <span class="cra-section-label-line"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="cra-decision-list">

      <div class="cra-decision-card">
        <div class="cra-decision-header">
          <span class="cra-decision-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-title">ASP.NET MVC 5 Over .NET Core</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-problem">The project started in 2019 when .NET Core 3.x was still maturing. The client infrastructure was Windows Server with IIS-only deployment. The existing enterprise ecosystem (SSIS, SSRS, Windows Services) required full .NET Framework compatibility.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-chosen"> Chosen — .NET Framework 4.5/4.8</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">MVC 5 provided mature tooling, Windows-native SSIS/SSRS integration, and seamless Windows Service deployment for Quartz scheduler. SimpleInjector DI, EF 6 Database-First, and NLog all had proven production track records on full Framework.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — .NET Core 3.x</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">Would have enabled cross-platform deployment, better performance, and modern middleware pipeline. However, SSIS/SSRS Windows-only dependency, team expertise in .NET Framework, and IIS infrastructure made migration not cost-effective during the project lifecycle.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-code">
<pre><span class="cra-token-cm">// Global.asax — SimpleInjector DI setup</span>
<span class="cra-token-kw">protected void</span> <span class="cra-token-fn">Application_Start</span>()
&#123;
    <span class="cra-token-fn">ConfigureDI</span>();
    <span class="cra-token-fn">AreaRegistration</span>.<span class="cra-token-fn">RegisterAllAreas</span>();
    <span class="cra-token-fn">FilterConfig</span>.<span class="cra-token-fn">RegisterGlobalFilters</span>(GlobalFilters.Filters);
    <span class="cra-token-fn">RouteConfig</span>.<span class="cra-token-fn">RegisterRoutes</span>(RouteTable.Routes);
    <span class="cra-token-fn">BundleConfig</span>.<span class="cra-token-fn">RegisterBundles</span>(BundleTable.Bundles);
&#125;

<span class="cra-token-kw">private void</span> <span class="cra-token-fn">ConfigureDI</span>()
&#123;
    <span class="cra-token-kw">var</span> container = <span class="cra-token-kw">new</span> <span class="cra-token-fn">Container</span>();
    container.<span class="cra-token-fn">Register</span>&lt;IUnitOfWork, UnitOfWork&gt;(Lifestyle.Scoped);
    container.<span class="cra-token-fn">Register</span>&lt;IPIBService, PIBService&gt;(Lifestyle.Scoped);
    <span class="cra-token-cm">// 56+ service registrations</span>
    container.<span class="cra-token-fn">Verify</span>();
    DependencyResolver.<span class="cra-token-fn">SetResolver</span>(<span class="cra-token-kw">new</span> <span class="cra-token-fn">SimpleInjectorDependencyResolver</span>(container));
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cra-decision-card">
        <div class="cra-decision-header">
          <span class="cra-decision-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-title">EF Database-First Over Code-First</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-problem">The CRA database schema was pre-existing and managed by a separate DBA team. 90+ tables with complex relationships, stored procedures, and views were already in production. Code-First would have required full schema redesign and migration management.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-chosen"> Chosen — EF 6 Database-First (EDMX)</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">EDMX with T4 templates auto-generated entity classes, complex types, and navigation properties from the existing database. Repository + Unit of Work patterns abstracted data access. SQL views and stored procedures were consumed directly via SqlQuery and SP repositories.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — EF Core Code-First</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">Code-First would have provided better migration management, LINQ improvements, and reduced EDMX bloat. However, the DBA-controlled schema with regular changes from SAP DBAs meant Database-First was more practical — schema changes were applied externally and EDMX updated to match.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-code">
<pre><span class="cra-token-cm">// Generic repository with Unit of Work</span>
<span class="cra-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="cra-token-fn">GenericRepository</span>&lt;T&gt; : IGenericRepository&lt;T&gt; <span class="cra-token-kw">where</span> T : <span class="cra-token-kw">class</span>
&#123;
    <span class="cra-token-kw">private readonly</span> CRAEntities _context;
    <span class="cra-token-kw">private readonly</span> DbSet&lt;T&gt; _dbSet;

    <span class="cra-token-kw">public virtual</span> IEnumerable&lt;T&gt; <span class="cra-token-fn">Get</span>(out <span class="cra-token-kw">int</span> total,
        Expression&lt;Func&lt;T, <span class="cra-token-kw">bool</span>&gt;&gt; filter = <span class="cra-token-kw">null</span>,
        Func&lt;IQueryable&lt;T&gt;, IOrderedQueryable&lt;T&gt;&gt; orderBy = <span class="cra-token-kw">null</span>,
        <span class="cra-token-kw">int</span>? page = <span class="cra-token-kw">null</span>, <span class="cra-token-kw">int</span>? pageSize = <span class="cra-token-kw">null</span>)
    &#123;
        IQueryable&lt;T&gt; query = _dbSet;
        <span class="cra-token-cm">// Dynamic filtering, sorting, paging</span>
    &#125;
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cra-decision-card">
        <div class="cra-decision-header">
          <span class="cra-decision-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-title">Dual UI Layer — jQuery DataTables + Kendo UI</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-problem">The application needed both simple data grids for master data (users, rates, configs) and complex interactive grids for reconciliation with inline editing, grouping, export, and real-time updates. A one-size-fits-all UI approach would have been suboptimal.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-chosen"> Chosen — DataTables + Kendo UI hybrid</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">jQuery DataTables with yadcf filtering provided fast, server-side paged grids for 40+ master data screens. Kendo UI was reserved for the complex reconciliation modules requiring inline editing, hierarchy, export to Excel, and advanced interaction patterns via Knockout.js MVVM binding.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — Pure SPA (React/Angular)</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">A SPA approach would have provided better UX consistency but required significant retraining of the team and a complete rewrite of the existing ASP.NET team's workflow. The hybrid approach let the team use familiar jQuery for simple screens and Kendo for complex ones.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-code">
<pre><span class="cra-token-cm">// DataTable with yadcf server-side filtering</span>
$().<span class="cra-token-fn">ready</span>(<span class="cra-token-kw">function</span> () &#123;
    <span class="cra-token-kw">var</span> table = $(<span class="cra-token-str">'#table'</span>).<span class="cra-token-fn">DataTable</span>(&#123;
        processing: <span class="cra-token-kw">true</span>,
        serverSide: <span class="cra-token-kw">true</span>,
        ajax: &#123; url: <span class="cra-token-str">'@Url.Action("GetData")'</span>, type: <span class="cra-token-str">'POST'</span> &#125;,
        columns: [<span class="cra-token-cm">/* 15+ column defs */</span>]
    &#125;);
    <span class="cra-token-fn">yadcf</span>.<span class="cra-token-fn">init</span>(table, [
        &#123; column_number: 1, filter_type: <span class="cra-token-str">'text'</span> &#125;,
        &#123; column_number: 2, filter_type: <span class="cra-token-str">'select'</span>, data: <span class="cra-token-fn">getUniqueValues</span>(<span class="cra-token-str">'AjuNumber'</span>) &#125;
    ]);
&#125;);</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cra-decision-card">
        <div class="cra-decision-header">
          <span class="cra-decision-num">04</span>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-title">Quartz.NET Windows Services for Batch Processing</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-problem">SAP team generated XML/EDI files into network folders on an hourly basis. These files needed to be picked up, parsed, reconciled, and loaded into the CRA database. A manual process would have required full-time headcount and introduced delays.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-chosen"> Chosen — Quartz.NET + Windows Service</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">Two Windows Services were built — a batch processor (XML/EDI parsing, SAP data loading, reconciliation execution) and a scheduler (Quartz job management with configurable triggers). 23 executor classes handled different SAP transaction types with fail/archive/retry logic.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-label cra-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — Hangfire / Azure Functions</div>
            <div class="cra-decision-col-text">Hangfire would have provided a built-in dashboard and simpler setup, but Quartz was already proven in the organization. Azure Functions required cloud migration. Windows Services integrated naturally with the existing IIS/Windows Server infrastructure.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cra-decision-code">
<pre><span class="cra-token-cm">// Quartz job for PIB EDI file processing</span>
<span class="cra-token-kw">public class</span> <span class="cra-token-fn">JobSchedulerPIB</span> : IJob
&#123;
    <span class="cra-token-kw">public async</span> Task <span class="cra-token-fn">Execute</span>(IJobExecutionContext context)
    &#123;
        <span class="cra-token-kw">var</span> config = <span class="cra-token-fn">GetFileConfig</span>(<span class="cra-token-str">"PIB_EDI"</span>);
        <span class="cra-token-kw">var</span> files = Directory.<span class="cra-token-fn">GetFiles</span>(config.InputPath, <span class="cra-token-str">"*.xml"</span>);

        <span class="cra-token-kw">foreach</span> (<span class="cra-token-kw">var</span> file <span class="cra-token-kw">in</span> files)
        &#123;
            <span class="cra-token-kw">try</span>
            &#123;
                <span class="cra-token-kw">var</span> executor = <span class="cra-token-fn">GetExecutor</span>(config.Type);
                <span class="cra-token-fn">executor</span>.<span class="cra-token-fn">Reader</span>(file);
                File.<span class="cra-token-fn">Move</span>(file, config.ArchivePath);
            &#125;
            <span class="cra-token-kw">catch</span>
            &#123;
                File.<span class="cra-token-fn">Move</span>(file, config.ErrorPath);
            &#125;
        &#125;
    &#125;
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

